  "texts": [
    "The goals of red-teaming activities also ranged from specific objectives (e.g., red-teaming to investigate risks to national security [8]) to more broad targets (e.g., uncovering \"harmful\" model behavior [150]); threat models related to the latter were more common.",
    "Model developers use such threat models for evaluation in hopes that this will yield greater variation in red-teaming efforts, especially because it is impossible to understand the model's entire risk surface.",
    "Unfortunately, probing these nonspecific threat models does not always produce this desired variation, more so when evaluators are given limited time and resources to produce harmful outputs.",
    "For example, some time-boxed evaluators repeatedly probed models in the same risk area because it was easy to produce harmful outputs, as opposed to exploring other risks [57].Interconnected members, resources, and outcomes.",
    "The evaluators employed in red-teaming activities for each case study varied considerably."
